Attribute.AttrValue: Rights of the Sovereign and the Duchy of Cornwall Bill [HL]

ParaLine.String: mend the Sovereign Grant Act 2011; amend the succession to the title of the
Duke of Cornwall; re-distribute the Duchy of Cornwall estate; and to remove
the requirement for a Parliament to obtain Queen or Prince\xd5 s consent to
consideration of bills passing through Parliament.
\xd5 s most Excellent Majesty, by and with the advice and
consent of the Lords Spiritual and Temporal, and Commons, in this present
Parliament assembled, and by the authority of the same, as follows:
Amendment to the Sovereign Grant Act 2011
Section 1 of the Sovereign Grant Act 2011 (the sovereign grant) is amended as
In subsection (2), after \xd2 Her Majesty\xd5 s\xd3 insert \xd2 and the Duke of Cornwall\xd5 s\xd3 .
After subsection (2), insert the following new subsections
The Sovereign Grant may only be used to fund official Royal travel for
persons who are one of the six persons next in the line of Succession to
\xd2 Official Royal travel\xd3 in subsection (2A) means
travel by air and rail by members of the Royal Family in
travel by air and rail by senior members of the Royal Family

Amendments to the Duchy of Cornwall estate
A Charter of 1337 shall be read as follows.
Where the Charter refers to the title of the Duke of Cornwall being inherited by
eldest sons of the Monarch, who are heir apparent, this shall be amended to
read that the title of the Duke of Cornwall shall be passed to the eldest child of
the monarch regardless of their gender.
The assets and property of the Duchy of Cornwall shall be transferred to and
shall vest in a public trust for the benefit of the people of Cornwall and the Isles
The Secretary of State may by order make provision as to the public trust

Splitting can occur anywhere within the Part/Chapter/CrossHeading structure of the clauses, or between Schedules. A split will never occur within a Schedule. Typically the split is only required for long Bills (e.g. Fincance Bill) where there is a physical limit to the number of pages that can be stapled by the printer.
